# Supabase Migrations — Consolidation Policy

The repository keeps schema in migrations under `supabase/migrations/`:

- `00000000000000_baseline.sql` — consolidated schema (tables, RLS, triggers)

Reference data lives in `supabase/seed.sql` (operating hours, menu items).

`supabase db reset --local` runs every file in lexicographic order, so
migrations should remain idempotent where possible (`CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS`,
`DROP POLICY IF EXISTS` + `CREATE POLICY`, `CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION`,
`ALTER TABLE … ADD COLUMN IF NOT EXISTS`).

## Default — Extend existing migrations

Whenever possible, do **not** add a new timestamped migration file or
maintenance script. Instead, fold the change into the migration that
owns the affected objects:

- New columns / RLS policies on an existing table → edit the migration that
  creates that table (or the most recent migration touching it).
- New storage buckets / bucket policies → extend the migration that owns
  storage or supporting tables.
- New triggers / functions → extend the migration that owns those objects.
- Updates to existing functions → modify the function definition in place; do
  not re-declare it in a new file.

When you extend a migration, prefer comments that tag the originating Linear
issue (e.g. `-- REAZED-12: blocked-date service policy`) for traceability.

## When a new dated migration is acceptable

Only add a new `YYYYMMDDHHMMSS_<slug>.sql` file when **all** of the following
are true:

1. The change cannot be expressed idempotently inside an existing migration (e.g.
   one-shot data backfill, destructive `DROP TABLE`, or a column rename that
   needs ordered DDL).
2. The change must run against an already-deployed environment where the
   existing migrations have been applied — i.e. you genuinely need a forward-only
   migration, not a rebuildable schema definition.
3. You have considered and documented why folding the change into an existing
   migration is unsafe.

If you do create a new file, copy the change into the appropriate existing
migration at the same time so a fresh `supabase db reset --local` produces an
equivalent schema, and follow up by retiring/squashing the dated file once it
has been applied to all environments.

## Avoid out-of-band schema scripts

- Do not add schema SQL under `scripts/`; that directory is for ad-hoc
  utilities only.
- Do not introduce parallel migration runners or `psql` snippets in the app —
  the Supabase CLI is the single source of truth.

## Verification checklist

After editing a migration, run:

```powershell
npx supabase db reset --local
npx supabase db lint --local --fail-on error
```

`db reset` must succeed in a single pass and re-running it on the same
database must remain a no-op. `db lint` should report zero errors before the
change is merged.
